  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">In this letter, Abby Kelley Foster calls attention to the anti-slavery cause in New York, where &quot;the lines between the old organization and Liberty Party and the Leaguers are not well drawn.&quot; She does not consider Joseph C. Hathaway qualified for the work there. Stephen S. Foster suggests Parker Pillsbury. Abby K. Foster is troubled by Frederick Douglass starting a paper in Cleveland. She believes that two disunion papers cannot be sustained in the west, and is afraid that Douglass&apos;s paper will supplant the Anti-Slavery Bugle. Confidentially, Abby Kelley Foster has always feared Douglass and believes that the &quot;manner of his proceeding in this matter was not quite honorable to say the least.&quot; He consulted none of the more active western abolitionists except Samuel Brooke. Abby K. Foster asks that Maria W. Chapman inform her of Mary Howitt&apos;s address and to send &quot;the controversy between the Howitt&apos;s and the People&apos;s Journal.&quot; [For more about the connection of Samuel Brooke and the founding of the North Star, see William Lloyd Garrison, III, p. 210-211.]</subfield>
